    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>What is the main difference between stocks and bonds?</summary>
        <p>Stocks represent an ownership stake (equity) in a company, while bonds represent a loan (debt) made by an investor to a borrower (corporate or governmental).</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Which is riskier, stocks or bonds?</summary>
        <p>Stocks are generally riskier because equity holders are last in line to be paid if a company goes bankrupt, and stock prices are highly volatile. Bonds are generally safer fixed-income instruments.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How do returns differ between stocks and bonds?</summary>
        <p>Historically, stocks have provided higher average annual returns over the long term to compensate for their higher risk, while bonds offer lower, more predictable returns.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Do bonds pay dividends?</summary>
        <p>No, bonds pay periodic 'interest' or 'coupon' payments. Stocks are the instruments that may pay 'dividends' from company profits.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Why should I own both stocks and bonds?</summary>
        <p>Holding both creates a diversified portfolio. Stocks provide growth potential, while bonds provide stability and income, smoothing out overall portfolio volatility.</p>
      </details>
